<h2>How can I tell if the compressor is failing?</h2>
<p>To determine if the compressor in your refrigerator is failing, look for the following signs:</p>
<p>1. <strong>Unusual Noises</strong>: If you hear loud or strange noises such as knocking, clanking, or humming coming
  from the back of the refrigerator, it could indicate that the compressor is struggling or failing.</p>
<p>2. <strong>Warm Refrigerator</strong>: One of the most obvious signs of a failing compressor is if your refrigerator
  isn't keeping your food cold. If you notice that the interior is warmer than usual, the compressor might not be
  functioning properly.</p>
<p>3. <strong>Frequent Cycling</strong>: A compressor that frequently turns on and off or runs continuously without
  cycling off may be experiencing issues. This can lead to inefficient cooling and higher energy bills.</p>
<p>4. <strong>Overheating</strong>: If the compressor is hot to the touch, it could be an indication of a problem. While
  compressors do generate some heat, excessive heat is not normal and could suggest a failing unit.</p>
<p>5. <strong>Tripped Circuit Breaker</strong>: If the circuit breaker for the refrigerator frequently trips, it could
  be due to the compressor drawing too much power, indicating a potential failure.</p>
<p>6. <strong>Clicking Sounds</strong>: If you hear a clicking noise when the compressor attempts to start but it
  doesn't run, it could be a sign that the compressor is failing or has already failed.</p>
<p>7. <strong>Leaks</strong>: While not directly related to the compressor itself, refrigerant leaks can cause the
  compressor to fail. If you notice any oily residue or leaks around the compressor, it could be a sign of trouble.</p>
